To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a ban command, follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have Node.js installed. You can download it from https://nodejs.org/

2. Next, create a new folder for your bot project and navigate to it in your terminal.

3. Run `npm init -y` to create a package.json file. This file will contain the necessary information about your bot and its dependencies.

4. Install the necessary dependencies: Discord.js and @discordjs/builders. Run the following command to install them:
```
npm install discord.js @discordjs/builders @discordjs/rest discord-api-types
```

5. Create a new file called `index.js` in your bot folder. Open it and paste the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents } = require('discord.js');
const { REST } = require('@discordjs/rest');
const { Routes } = require('discord-api-types/v9');
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require('@discordjs/builders');

const clientId = 'YOUR_BOT_CLIENT_ID';
const guildId = 'YOUR_GUILD_ID';
const token = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN';

const commands = [
  new SlashCommandBuilder().setName('ban').setDescription('Ban a user').addUserOption(option => option.setName('user').setDescription('The user to ban').setRequired(true)).toJSON(),
];

const rest = new REST({ version: '9' }).setToken(token);

(async () => {
  try {
    console.log('Started refreshing application (/) commands.');

    await rest.put(
      Routes.applicationGuildCommands(clientId, guildId),
      { body: commands },
    );

    console.log('Successfully reloaded application (/) commands.');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
})();

const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MEMBERS, Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MESSAGES, Intents.FLAGS.GUILDS] });

client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const { commandName } = interaction;

  if (commandName === 'ban') {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');

    if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      return await interaction.reply('You do not have permission to ban members.');
    }

    const member = interaction.guild.members.resolve(user.id);

    if (!member) {
      return await interaction.reply('User not found in the server.');
    }

    if (!member.bannable) {
      return await interaction.reply('I cannot ban this user.');
    }

    await member.ban();
    await interaction.reply(`Successfully banned ${user.tag}.`);
  }
});

client.login(token);
```

6. Replace `YOUR_BOT_CLIENT_ID`, `YOUR_GUILD_ID`, and `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your bot's client ID, your server's guild ID, and your bot's token, respectively. You can find these values in the Discord Developer Portal (https://discord.com/developers/applications).

7. Run your bot with `node index.js`. Your bot should now be online and respond to the `/ban` command when you use it in your server.

Here's a simple C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text. This function only supports basic Markdown features such as headings, bold, italic, and links.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // Replace headings
    for (int i = 6; i >= 1; --i) {
        std::regex heading_regex("(^|\n)" + std::string(i, '#') + " (.+)");
        html = std::regex_replace(html, heading_regex, "$1<h" + std::to_string(i) + ">$2</h" + std::to_string(i) + ">");
    }

    // Replace bold text
    std::regex bold_regex(R"(\*\*(.+?)\*\*)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, bold_regex, "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Replace italic text
    std::regex italic_regex(R"(\*(.+?)\*)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, italic_regex, "<em>$1</em>");

    // Replace links
    std::regex link_regex(R"(\[(.+?)\]\((.+?)\))");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, link_regex, "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown_text = R"(# Heading 1
## Heading 2
### Heading 3
**Bold text**
*Italic text*
[Link text](https://www.example.com))";

    std::string html_text = markdownToHtml(markdown_text);
    std::cout << html_text << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Please note that this implementation is not a complete Markdown to HTML converter and only supports a limited set of Markdown features. For a comprehensive Markdown to HTML conversion in C++, consider using an existing library like [cpp-markdown](https://github.com/Kyoma/cpp-markdown) or [cmark](https://github.com/commonmark/cmark).

Creating a smooth snake game in C with image animations requires using a game library that supports image rendering and more advanced game loop features. We'll use SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer), a cross-platform development library designed for games and multimedia applications.

1. Install SDL2 library:
First, you need to install the SDL2 library and its extension for image loading. Follow the instructions on the SDL website (https://www.libsdl.org/download-2.0.php) for your platform.

2. Set up the project:
Create a new project in your favorite C IDE and include the SDL2 header files and libraries according to your platform's instructions.

3. Create game resources:
Prepare the images required for your snake game, such as the snake's body parts, food, and background. Save these images in a folder named "resources" in your project directory.

4. Start coding the snake game:

```c
#include <SDL.h>
#include <SDL_image.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <time.h>

// Define window and renderer
SDL_Window *window = NULL;
SDL_Renderer *renderer = NULL;

// Define game variables
const int WINDOW_WIDTH = 800;
const int WINDOW_HEIGHT = 600;
const int SNAKE_SIZE = 32;
const int FPS = 60;

// Snake direction
typedef enum { UP, DOWN, LEFT, RIGHT } Direction;
Direction snake_dir = RIGHT;

// Snake structure
typedef struct Snake {
    int x, y;
    struct Snake *next;
} Snake;

// Initialize the game
bool init() {
    // Initialize SDL
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) < 0) {
        printf("SDL could not initialize! SDL Error: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        return false;
    }

    // Create window
    window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, WINDOW_WIDTH, WINDOW_HEIGHT, SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN);
    if (!window) {
        printf("Window could not be created! SDL Error: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        return false;
    }

    // Create renderer
    renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (!renderer) {
        printf("Renderer could not be created! SDL Error: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        return false;
    }

    // Initialize SDL_image
    int imgFlags = IMG_INIT_PNG;
    if (!(IMG_Init(imgFlags) & imgFlags)) {
        printf("SDL_image could not initialize! SDL_image Error: %s\n", IMG_GetError());
        return false;
    }

    return true;
}

// Load image resources
SDL_Texture *loadTexture(const char *path) {
    SDL_Surface *loadedSurface = IMG_Load(path);
    if (!loadedSurface) {
        printf("Unable to load image %s! SDL_image Error: %s\n", path, IMG_GetError());
        return NULL;
    }

    SDL_Texture *texture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(renderer, loadedSurface);
    SDL_FreeSurface(loadedSurface);

    return texture;
}

// Main function
int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    srand(time(NULL));

    if (!init()) {
        printf("Failed to initialize!\n");
        return 1;
    }

    // Load resources
    SDL_Texture *snakeBodyTexture = loadTexture("resources/snake_body.png");
    SDL_Texture *snakeHeadTexture = loadTexture("resources/snake_head.png");
    SDL_Texture *foodTexture = loadTexture("resources/food.png");
    SDL_Texture *backgroundTexture = loadTexture("resources/background.png");

    // Initialize game objects
    Snake *snake_head = (Snake *)malloc(sizeof(Snake));
    snake_head->x = WINDOW_WIDTH / 2;
    snake_head->y = WINDOW_HEIGHT / 2;
    snake_head->next = NULL;

    Snake *food = (Snake *)malloc(sizeof(Snake));
    food->x = rand() % (WINDOW_WIDTH / SNAKE_SIZE) * SNAKE_SIZE;
    food->y = rand() % (WINDOW_HEIGHT / SNAKE_SIZE) * SNAKE_SIZE;
    food->next = NULL;

    // Main game loop
    bool quit = false;
    SDL_Event e;
    Uint32 frame_start, frame_time;
    int frame_delay = 1000 / FPS;

    while (!quit) {
        frame_start = SDL_GetTicks();

        // Event handling
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&e) != 0) {
            if (e.type == SDL_QUIT) {
                quit = true;
            } else if (e.type == SDL_KEYDOWN) {
                // Handle input
                switch (e.key.keysym.sym) {
                    case SDLK_UP:
                        if (snake_dir != DOWN) snake_dir = UP;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_DOWN:
                        if (snake_dir != UP) snake_dir = DOWN;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_LEFT:
                        if (snake_dir != RIGHT) snake_dir = LEFT;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_RIGHT:
                        if (snake_dir != LEFT) snake_dir = RIGHT;
                        break;
                }
            }
        }

        // Game logic here

        // Render the game
        SDL_RenderClear(renderer);
        // Render background
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, backgroundTexture, NULL, NULL);

        // Render snake
        for (Snake *snake = snake_head; snake != NULL; snake = snake->next) {
            SDL_Rect snakeRect = {snake->x, snake->y, SNAKE_SIZE, SNAKE_SIZE};
            if (snake == snake_head) {
                SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snakeHeadTexture, NULL, &snakeRect);
            } else {
                SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snakeBodyTexture, NULL, &snakeRect);
            }
        }

        // Render food
        SDL_Rect foodRect = {food->x, food->y, SNAKE_SIZE, SNAKE_SIZE};
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, foodTexture, NULL, &foodRect);

        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);

        // Cap the frame rate
        frame_time = SDL_GetTicks() - frame_start;
        if (frame_delay > frame_time) {
            SDL_Delay(frame_delay - frame_time);
        }
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_DestroyTexture(snakeBodyTexture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(snakeHeadTexture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(foodTexture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(backgroundTexture);

    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);

    IMG_Quit();
    SDL_Quit();

    return 0;
}
```

This code initializes the SDL window and renderer, loads the images, and renders the game objects. You'll need to implement the game logic for the snake's movement, collision detection, and food consumption.

Remember to link the SDL2 library and the SDL2_image library and include the header files when compiling the code.

