In Java, when comparing strings, it is important to understand the difference between the `==` operator and the `.equals()` method.

The `==` operator is used to compare reference variables, i.e., it checks if two variables are referencing the same object in memory. It does not compare the content of the strings. Therefore, using `==` to compare strings can lead to unexpected results, especially when the strings have the same content but are different objects in memory.

On the other hand, the `.equals()` method is used to compare the content of the strings. It checks if two strings have the same sequence of characters, irrespective of their memory location. This is the recommended way to compare strings in Java.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = new String("Hello");

// Using == operator
boolean result1 = (str1 == str2); // result1 will be false, because str1 and str2 reference different objects in memory

// Using .equals() method
boolean result2 = str1.equals(str2); // result2 will be true, because the content of str1 and str2 is the same
```

In summary, you should avoid using the `==` operator to compare strings in Java. Instead, use the `.equals()` method to compare the content of the strings.

